In 1902 a [[Prospecting|prospector]], John Karshner, discovered several hot springs in the area. He began a [[Homestead Act|homestead]] and vegetable farm. In the same year, the United States Army built a [[telegraph]] station. The area became a service and supply point for miners in the [[Tofty, Alaska|Tofty]] and Eureka mining districts. It was known as Baker's Hot Springs, after nearby Baker Creek.


Farming and livestock operations in the area produced fresh meat, poultry, and produce for sale. In 1903, Sam's Rooms and Meals, now called the Manley Roadhouse, opened. The [[Roadhouse (premises)|roadhouse]] was owned by Robert E. Lee, who was also the town's postmaster until his death in 2010. In 1907 a miner named Frank Manley built the Hot Springs Resort Hotel. The resort was a four-story building with 45 guest rooms, steam heat, electric lights, hot baths, a bar, a restaurant, a billiard room, a bowling alley, a barber shop, and an Olympic-size indoor swimming pool which used heated water from the hot springs. During the summer, the hotel's private boat transported guests from steamers on the [[Tanana River]]. In the winter, an overland stagecoach trip from [[Fairbanks]] took two days. The town was renamed ''Hot Springs''.

During the summer, the hotel's private boat transported guests from steamers on the [[Tanana River]]. In the winter, an overland stagecoach trip from [[Fairbanks]] took two days. The town was renamed ''Hot Springs''.


The resort and the mining in the area caused the town to prosper. It had a store, a newspaper, a bakery, clothing stores and other businesses. The population of the area in 1910 was more than 500. In 1913 the resort burned to the ground. Mining activity was also in decline and by 1920 only 29 residents lived in Hot Springs.

Monroe Elementary School is connected to the broader impact of the U.S. Supreme Court’s 1954 decision in ''Brown v. Board of Education'', which declared racial segregation in public schools unconstitutional. While Iowa did not maintain legally segregated school systems, segregation in Davenport existed in practice through residential patterns and school attendance boundaries, resulting in schools such as Monroe serving disproportionately African American student populations.

Following ''Brown v. Board of Education'', school districts across the country, including those in states without statutory segregation, faced increased pressure to address racial imbalances and inequalities in educational resources. In Davenport, the ruling prompted renewed attention to school zoning, student distribution, and equal access to facilities. Monroe Elementary’s student population and neighborhood context placed it within these post-''Brown'' discussions about educational equity and integration.

During the decades after the decision, Monroe Elementary continued to serve as an important neighborhood school while the Davenport Community School District gradually implemented policies intended to reduce racial and economic disparities among its schools. As a result, the building represents the local, incremental effects of ''Brown v. Board of Education'' in northern and Midwestern cities, where segregation was shaped more by housing discrimination than by explicit law.

Monroe Elementary School thus reflects how the legacy of ''Brown'' extended beyond the South, influencing educational policy and community experiences in cities such as Davenport and highlighting the ongoing challenges of achieving truly integrated public education.

==== Grooming policy controversy ====
Few sparked a long-simmering legal problem for the department when he began implementing in March 2001 a never-enforced 1977 policy requiring all DCFEMS personnel to have short hair and trimmed beards. Three firefighters were suspended and a number of others threatened with suspension for refusing to adhere to the policy. Few claimed firefighters were unable to wear their helmets or properly seal their safety helmets due to over-long hair.<ref name="SantanaPolicy" /><ref>Holly, Derrill. "Union Challenges D.C. Fire Department Grooming Policy". ''Associated Press.'' April 3, 2001; Santana, Arthur. "While Focusing on Hair, D.C. Skips Fire Mask Safety Test". ''Washington Post''. April 6, 2001.</ref> However, on June 21, 2001, Judge [[James Robertson (judge)|James Robertson]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] imposed a [[injunction|temporary injunction]] against the department, preventing it from applying the short-hair policy to those individuals (such as [[Rastafari movement|Rastafarians]] or [[Islam|Muslims]]) who wore long hair or beards for religious purposes.<ref>Greenfield, Heather. "Judge Boots Grooming Policy for D.C. Firefighters". ''Associated Press.'' June 22, 2001.</ref> Judge Robertson's ruling only delayed a final disposition regarding the policy, however, and appeals were made.
Few turned a latent legal problem into an active one in March 2001, when he began implementing a never-enforced 1977 policy requiring DCFEMS personnel to have short hair and trimmed beards. Three firefighters were suspended and others threatened with suspension for refusing to adhere to the policy. Chief Few claimed firefighters were unable to wear their helmets or properly seal their safety helmets due to over-long hair.<ref name="SantanaPolicy" /><ref>Holly, Derrill. "Union Challenges D.C. Fire Department Grooming Policy". ''Associated Press.'' April 3, 2001; Santana, Arthur. "While Focusing on Hair, D.C. Skips Fire Mask Safety Test". ''Washington Post''. April 6, 2001.</ref> On June 21, 2001, Judge [[James Robertson (judge)|James Robertson]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] imposed a [[injunction|temporary injunction]] against the department, preventing it from applying the short-hair policy to people (such as [[Rastafari movement|Rastafarians]] or [[Islam|Muslims]]) who wore long hair or beards for religious purposes.<ref>Greenfield, Heather. "Judge Boots Grooming Policy for D.C. Firefighters". ''Associated Press.'' June 22, 2001.</ref>


A May 2001 performance report showed that the D.C. fire department was deteriorating rapidly under Few's leadership. Halfway through the budget year, Few met only one of four major goals (filling 120 firefighter vacancies). The number of injuries to firefighters and civilian injuries and deaths had far outstripped the year's goals, and building inspections were far below the expected level. Ambulances were supposed to reach patients 90 percent of the time within eight minutes. Few changed this to 70 percent without explanation, and still the department could not reach the goal. The department was also caught manipulating data in an attempt to improve the response times. (For example, fire engines with paramedics aboard often responded faster to a medical emergency than a paramedic-driven ambulance with life-saving equipment. DCFEMS began incorporating fire engine response times and neglected to make the changed clear.)<ref>Drake, John. "Few Fails to Meet Own Lower Standards". ''Washington Times''. May 22, 2001.</ref>
